{"title":"Review: The fastest of the M4 MacBook Pros might be the least interesting one","link":"https://arstechnica.com/apple/2024/11/review-the-fastest-of-the-m4-macbook-pros-might-be-the-least-interesting-one/","date":1731436894000,"content":"<p>In some ways, my review of the new MacBook Pros will be a lot like my review of the new iMac. This is the third year and fourth generation of the <a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2021/10/2021-macbook-pro-review-yep-its-what-youve-been-waiting-for/\">Apple Silicon-era MacBook Pro design</a>, and outwardly, few things have changed about the new M4, M4 Pro, and M4 Max laptops.</p>\n<p>Here are the things that are different. Boosted RAM capacities, across the entire lineup but most crucially in the entry-level $1,599 M4 MacBook Pro, make the new laptops a shade cheaper and more versatile than they used to be. The new nano-texture display option, a $150 upgrade on all models, is a lovely matte-textured coating that completely eliminates reflections. There's a third Thunderbolt port on the baseline M4 model (the M3 model had two), and it can drive up to three displays simultaneously (two external, plus the built-in screen). There's a new webcam. It looks a little nicer and has a wide-angle lens that can show what's on your desk instead of your face if you want it to. And there are new chips, which we'll get to.</p>\n<figure>\n      <img width=\"1024\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2425-1024x576.jpeg\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2425-1024x576.jpeg 1024w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2425-640x360.jpeg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2425-768x432.jpeg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2425-1536x864.jpeg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2425-2048x1152.jpeg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2425-384x216.jpeg 384w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2425-1152x648.jpeg 1152w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2425-980x551.jpeg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2425-1440x810.jpeg 1440w\" />\n      <figcaption>\n        <div>\n    <div></div>\n    <div>\n      Keyboard and trackpad. The 16-inch model looks the same, just with a bigger trackpad. \n\n              <span>\n          Credit:\n\n          \n          Andrew Cunningham\n\n                  </span>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n      </figcaption>\n    </figure>\n      <figure>\n      <img width=\"1024\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2456-1024x576.jpeg\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2456-1024x576.jpeg 1024w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2456-640x360.jpeg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2456-768x432.jpeg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2456-1536x864.jpeg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2456-2048x1153.jpeg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2456-384x216.jpeg 384w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2456-1152x648.jpeg 1152w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2456-980x552.jpeg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2456-1440x811.jpeg 1440w\" />\n      <figcaption>\n        <div>\n    <div></div>\n    <div>\n      \"MacBook Pro\" is etched on the bottom of the laptops. \n\n              <span>\n          Credit:\n\n          \n          Andrew Cunningham\n\n                  </span>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n      </figcaption>\n    </figure>\n      <figure>\n      <img width=\"1024\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2457-1024x576.jpeg\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2457-1024x576.jpeg 1024w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2457-640x360.jpeg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2457-768x432.jpeg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2457-1536x864.jpeg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2457-2048x1153.jpeg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2457-384x216.jpeg 384w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2457-1152x648.jpeg 1152w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2457-980x552.jpeg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2457-1440x811.jpeg 1440w\" />\n      <figcaption>\n        <div>\n    <div></div>\n    <div>\n      Ports on the left: MagSafe, and two Thunderbolt 4 (for the M4) or Thunderbolt 5 (for the M4 Pro/M4 Max) ports.\n\n              <span>\n          Credit:\n\n          \n          Andrew Cunningham\n\n                  </span>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n      </figcaption>\n    </figure>\n      <figure>\n      <img width=\"1024\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2464-1024x576.jpeg\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2464-1024x576.jpeg 1024w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2464-640x360.jpeg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2464-768x432.jpeg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2464-1536x864.jpeg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2464-2048x1152.jpeg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2464-384x216.jpeg 384w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2464-1152x648.jpeg 1152w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2464-980x551.jpeg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_2464-1440x810.jpeg 1440w\" />\n      <figcaption>\n        <div>\n    <div></div>\n    <div>\n      On the right, an SD card reader, a Thunderbolt 4 or 5 port, and HDMI. \n\n              <span>\n          Credit:\n\n          \n          Andrew Cunningham\n\n                  </span>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n      </figcaption>\n    </figure>\n  \n<p>That is essentially the end of the list. If you are still using an Intel-era MacBook Pro, I'll <a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2021/10/2021-macbook-pro-review-yep-its-what-youve-been-waiting-for/\">point you</a> to our <a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2023/11/review-apples-16-inch-m3-max-macbook-pro-crams-ultra-level-speed-into-a-laptop/\">previous reviews</a>, which mostly celebrate the improvements (more and different kids of ports, larger screens) while picking one or two nits (they are a bit larger and heavier than late-Intel MacBook Pros, and the display notch is an eyesore).</p><p><a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/apple/2024/11/review-the-fastest-of-the-m4-macbook-pros-might-be-the-least-interesting-one/\">Read full article</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/apple/2024/11/review-the-fastest-of-the-m4-macbook-pros-might-be-the-least-interesting-one/#comments\">Comments</a></p>","author":"Andrew Cunningham","siteTitle":"Ars Technica","siteHash":"5b0ddf6e8923e49262a7894cfd77962733e43fbcc565a103b48373820b310636","entryHash":"9a15498191aec68c946f30fb935063c979e9040665760e62a49160de177b978d","category":"Tech"}